{{Infobox member of the Knesset |image = גרשון שפט. צילום אלי אלון.jpg |birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1927|12|6|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Vienna]], [[Austria]] |Year of Aliyah = 1934 |death_date = |death_place = |Knesset(s) = [[Israeli legislative election, 1984|11]], [[Israeli legislative election, 1988|12]] |party1 = [[Tehiya]] |partyyears1 = 1984–1992 }}
'''Gershon Shafat''' ({{lang-he|גרשון שפט}}, born 6 December 1927) is an [[Israel]]i former politician who served as a member of the [[Knesset]] for [[Tehiya]] during the mid–1980s and early 1990s.
==Biography== Born '''Gershon Staub''' in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]] in 1927, Shafat [[aliyah|emigrated]] to [[Mandatory Palestine]] in 1934. He was educated at the Moria high school in [[Tel Aviv]], and spent two years studying history and sociology at university.
He became a member of the [[Bnei Akiva]] youth movement, and later joined the [[National Religious Party]]. In 1946 he was amongst the founders of kibbutz [[Ein Tzurim]]. After the kibbutz was conquered by the [[Jordan]]ian Army, he was a [[prisoner of war]] for ten months.<ref>[https://www.knesset.gov.il/mk/eng/mk_eng.asp?mk_individual_id_t=659 Gershon Shafat: Public Activities] Knesset website</ref> When released, he was a member of the group that re-established Ein Tzurim in a new location.
From 1956 until 1958 he worked as the manager of the Purchasing Organisation, and as the Co-ordinator of the [[Religious Kibbutz Movement]]'s political committee. Between 1961 and 1977 he managed a Tadmor factory
In 1974 he became a member of the [[Gush Emunim]] [[Israeli settlement|settlement]] movement's secretariat, and held the post of political secretary between 1976 and 1979. He joined the new [[Tehiya]] party in 1979, and served as its secretary-general until 1985. Placed fifth on the party's list,<ref>[[Ian Lustick|Lustick, IS]] (1988) [http://www.polisci.upenn.edu/faculty/data/lustick/for_the_land/lustick13.html For The Land and The Lord: The Evolution of Gush Emunim] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612150545/http://www.polisci.upenn.edu/faculty/data/lustick/for_the_land/lustick13.html |date=2010-06-12 }}</ref> he was elected to the Knesset in [[Israeli legislative election, 1984|1984]], as Tehiya won five seats. Although he lost his seat in the [[Israeli legislative election, 1988|1988 elections]], he returned to the Knesset on 31 January 1990 as a replacement for [[Yuval Ne'eman]],<ref>[https://www.knesset.gov.il/mk/eng/mkindexbyknesset_eng.asp?knesset=12 Knesset Members in the Twelfth Knesset] Knesset website</ref> who had resigned his seat. Shafat lost his seat again in the [[Israeli legislative election, 1992|1992 elections]], in which Tehiya failed to cross the electoral threshold.
